You are only interacting with a single `ArrayList` instance, but calling it by different names. So when you print it, you&#39;re printing it at different stages of that object&#39;s lifetime, but it&#39;s still the same instance.

This line:

```
ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; arrayToAdd = lastArray;
```

does not make a copy of the object; it&#39;s just giving the same object a different name. You need to explicitly copy it. For example:

```
ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; arrayToAdd = new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;();
arrayToAdd.addAll(lastArray);
```

