By the way, your second example has incorrect values for variable `from` since there is no path from the root (node 1) to any other node (i.e. the value 1 is not present in variable `from`). 

If I understand your question correctly, you need to total path costs bottom up, i.e. starting with leaf nodes and working your way up to the root. This is a bit more complicated then computing total costs from the root to the leaves.

The solution requires that for each node we first compute its parent (I have renumbered every node to be origin-0 in the `parent` list). This is an O(N) operation. This allows us to walk the tree from leaf nodes up to the root accumulating costs as we go along. It is true that some nodes (those with two children) will be visited twice, but this is still an O(N) operation since the worst case the number of nodes visited will be &lt; 2*N.

```lang-Java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.HashSet;

public class Test {
    public int findValidPaths(int[] list, int[] from, int[] to, int k) {
        // Convert passed arguments into a tree:
        // Find leaves:
        HashSet&lt;Integer&gt; leaves = new HashSet&lt;Integer&gt;();
        for (int i: to)
            leaves.add(i - 1); // 0-origin
        HashSet&lt;Integer&gt; fromSet = new HashSet&lt;Integer&gt;();
        for (int i: from)
            fromSet.add(i - 1); // 0-origin
        leaves.removeAll(fromSet);
        int numNodes = list.length;
        int[] parent = new int[numNodes];
		parent[0] = -1; // root node has no parent
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; from.length; i++) {
            int fromNode = from[i] - 1; // 0-origin
            int toNode = to[i] - 1; // 0-origin
			parent[toNode] = fromNode;
        }
        int counter = 0;
		int nodesVisited = 0;
        for (int nodeNumber: leaves) {
			int totalCost = 0;
			while (nodeNumber != -1) {
				nodesVisited += 1;
				totalCost += list[nodeNumber];
				if (totalCost % k == 0)
					counter += 1;
				nodeNumber = parent[nodeNumber];
			}
		}
		System.out.printf(&quot;Total nodes: %d, Nodes visited: %d\n&quot;, numNodes, nodesVisited);
        return counter;
    }

    public void test1() {
        int[] list = {1, 1, 1, 1};
        int[] from = {1, 1, 4};
        int[] to = {2, 4, 3};
        int n = findValidPaths(list, from, to, 2);
