One way is to turn the tree upside-down and view it as a DAG (directed acyclic graph), meaning the links go from child to parent. We introduce a source node with links to all other nodes. The links between the source and any other node are a path.

To find all valid paths, we recursively traverse the DAG starting at the source node. At each node, we determine whether it is a valid path using the validity formula with the cost accumulated along the path up to that node. The recursion rewinds at the former root node.

If we count the number of valid paths as the recursion proceeds down, we can sum the counts from the different branches when it rewinds, ending up with the total when it finishes.

Once you have the DAG, this should be just a few lines of Java code.

---

I added a Java implementation using the DAG approach. I made it recursive first, but it seems Java does not optimize tail recursion, so I switched to iteration. I use only ints and int arrays to avoid time-consuming type-coercion between int and Integer. The code is as fast as it gets in Java, reminiscent of C. 

The complexity of the average height of a random binary tree with N nodes is O(logN) with high probability. If we use that as an upper bound for the average path length, the DAG approach becomes O(N*logN). The DAG approach is suitable for parallel execution, which makes complexity drop to O(logN). In practice, we do not have N processors, but the code becomes faster also with fewer.


